expl: The confused noise of children studying; dumb; to keep silent…
Ten, used after a higher number; an answer, a word of reply like Aye! [á꜅ ꜂hò], yes, well; [sz’꜄ á꜅ ꜁ts‘ín], forty cash
Read [áp꜆]. To instil, to saturate, to soak…
Bubbles on the water; frothy spume
A rank condiment of fish or flesh and salted hashed fine, with red rice and oil; [꜀chá ꜁ü], a sort of Medosa or sea-bluber; [lá꜅ ꜂chá], rank, dirty, foul.
A colloquial word. A door sill; a threshold; [꜃k‘í ꜁mún ꜃ch‘án], standing in the door-way.
to file
[ak꜆ ak꜆] the sound of giggling
A colloquial word. To cover, over, to keep from the air; to cover, as with a poultice;…
An unauthorized word. To profit, to make gain in trade; [chán꜅ ꜁ts‘ín], to make money; [꜀to chán꜅] profitable; [꜃mò tak꜆ chán꜅] no profit;…

To lead, to go before, to seduce or induce; a leader; an example, a guide; used for the last and next; [꜀ch‘éung tò꜅] to show the way; [꜀ch‘éung ꜀sín], to speak first; [꜀ch‘éung sut꜆], to lead on; [꜀ch‘éung ꜁t‘au], a leader; [꜀ch‘éung lün꜅] to head a riot.
A colloquial word. An interjection used in answers, senoting surprise or alarm; alas! dreadful
A colloquial partile implying a short time; [꜂tang ꜃há ꜀chá]! Wait a moment; [꜀yam ꜁ch‘á ꜀chá], only just to take a cup of tea
A colloquial word. To place, to put down, to put by; [꜀chai ꜁mái], put it aside; [꜀chai ꜀pín ch‘ü꜄], where shall I put it? [꜀chai ꜀pín ch‘ü꜄ ꜀tò ꜂hò], put in it down anywhere.
To sell goods at a profit
Groping, going blindly; madly, carelessly; to fall down; [꜁ch‘áng ꜂kwai], a lates eaten by a tiger, *met.* one who entices to evil courses
The wrangling of children; to open the mouth wide; [꜁ngá ꜀lán ꜃mai], cochineal
A colloquial word. A final particle, adding intensity to the meaning; [꜁’m ꜂hò á꜄] not at all good
A colloquial word… To deceive, to delude, to take in; [꜂kòm yéung꜅ ák꜆ ꜁yan ꜂ké] are you going to cheat him so!
A colloquial word. To thrust in, to put into, as a purse or drawer; [at꜆ lok꜇] put it in; [at꜆ ꜃k‘ü iú꜄] he must want it; make him take it
To soak, to macerate, to steep…
A colloquial word. A coat, as of paint; a thickness, an envelop, a skin; [ts‘at꜆ ꜀sám cham꜄] varnished it three times; [mok꜆ yat꜆ cham꜄ ꜁p‘í], pull off one covering
To verify, to prove; a prognostic; to fulfill; [ch‘am꜄ ꜃ü], a prophecy, a hidden meaning; [ch‘am꜄ hí꜄] tiresome, talkative; [ch‘am꜄ ꜂wai], to agree with the prophecy.
to pierce, to stab
A nest in the cave. Erroneously read [꜀wo] in the Fan Wan.

A portion, a dividend, a share… A vulgar character. An old form of 彬 [꜀pan]. The proper sound in colloquial is [fan꜅], though sometimes read [꜂fan]. It is the same word as 分 [fan꜅] when used as a noun.
A colloquial word. To whip, to spank, to punish
A colloquial word. Seems to be a mispronunciation of [fat꜆]; [꜀fá ꜀fá fik꜆ fik꜆] fickle, inconstant, fitful, never finishing anything
To brush off (as a fly); [fik꜆ ꜀hoi], brush it off!
A colloquial word. Confused, tangled; [꜀fing kòm꜄ lün꜅] all in disorder, as one moving; touzled, as hair
A colloquial word. A slap with the hand; [tái꜅] pa2 ~] a smart slap
A colloquial word. Top whip; to beat with a flat board; to beat up, as eggs or jelly; [fák꜆ ꜀kon tseng꜅] thrash it clean, as a carpet; [fák꜆ ꜂t‘ung], the tub into which grain is thrashed
Wrangling, noisy
A colloquial word. To vibrate, to swing, to dandle, as the end of a rope; to sprinkle; to snap away; to shake off, as ink out of a pen; [fing꜅ kwo꜄ ꜁lai] yerk it (as the cue) forward
A colloquial exclamation, expressing disapproval; [꜀hé]! [꜁’m ꜂hò t‘au꜄] don't touch it!
A colloquial word, to perk or cock up, as a dog's tail, a bow lying on its back, or the stern of a junk.
To swing; to shake in the wind; [꜁t‘iú ꜁t‘iú fing꜅] to hang and swing; [fing꜅ tik꜆ ꜂shui ꜁lai], sprinkle a little water; [fing꜅ lat꜆] shake it off
The hands rapidly moving
Read [fán꜄], in the phrase [fán꜄ fán꜄] an easy, even sound
Read [hang꜅] in colloquial. Tense, taut, drawn tight, as a drum or umbrella
The noise or roaring of water or waves; floating
A colloquial name for a weaver's reed or slaie
Same as 炎
A colloquial word. Uneven, interrupted; [lak꜆ k‘ak꜆] difficult, not smooth; [lò꜅ ꜂hò lak꜆ k‘ak꜆] the road is very rough; [꜂kong tak꜆ lak꜆ lak꜆ k‘ak꜆ k‘ak꜆] to stammer, to hesitate
A locust; [k‘ai꜄ ꜀chung], a large grasshopper
A sort of frog
Firm, durable, lasting; able to endure; enduring, well placed or settled…
A halo; [üt꜇ ꜃yau hung꜅] there is a halo round the moon
An exclamation; halloo, stop! [꜀hwé ꜃ní hü꜄ ꜀p‘ín] halloo! Where are you going?
Read [ín꜅] in the same sense as 現 [ín꜅].
Read [k‘ai꜄] , and used for 契
A colloquial word, and often pronunced [꜃k‘iú]. To wind around; [꜃k‘iú ꜀pín], to coil the cue around the head; [꜃k‘iú ꜂sín], to wind thread
Sams as 蚶, a species of Arca, or bivalves with furrowed shells
To awake
Grand, exalted; correct, upright; to understand, to perceive; intelligent…
The neck of a man.
Strong, overbearing, domineering; unbending; to oppose, to resist …
To pout; [꜀kù ꜂hí ꜂tsui], to pout out the lips.
Far; to go to a distance
A colloquial word. A bunch, a cluster; [yat꜆ ꜁k‘ung ꜀tsiú], a bunch of plantains…
Read [lap꜆] in the Fan Wan.
A colloquial word; quick, speedy; [꜀p‘an ꜀lan], in a hurry, quick

A colloquial word; a bazaar or row for the sale of an article; [꜁hám ꜀há ꜀lán], the salt-shrimp row; [꜁au ꜀lán ꜁mún], the Oil-row Gate on the south of Canton, called the Petition Gate; [lok꜇ ꜀lán hü꜅] gone to the bazaar; [꜁mái ꜀lán], to take to the bazaar, to turn peddler; [꜂kwo ꜀lán], the fruit market
A lot of things tied together is called [kwáng꜄ lang꜄]
A colloquial word. To repeat, to reiterate; [lap꜇ tap꜆ ꜂kong], a needless repetition; …
The noise of waves; to confound, to mix; to unstop; to let flow out; to rise, to float; [kwat꜆ ꜀ch‘au], to confuse.

A colloquial word; see [nám꜄]|To overpass, to skip; to leap over; an interval; [lám꜄ yat꜇] every other day; [lám꜄ ch‘ut꜆ ꜁mún ꜂hau], he went out doors; [lám꜄ ꜀kò], to step high; [tái꜅ pò꜅ lám꜄] give a good leap and cross it
(This is read [꜃lang] in the Fan Wan.)
Leaven, yeast; it is the residuum left after distilling samshoo; … Read [꜂háu] in the Fan Wan
A colloquial sound, used in the phrase [꜂fo kí꜄] a comrade.
A colloquial word; the character is doubtful. In the house, at home, within doors; [uk꜆ ꜂k‘í] home, in the house; [꜁’m hai꜅ ꜂k‘í], he is not in.
A colloquial word; to bind, to take a loop, or tie up with a chain or cord; [kik꜆ chü꜅ ꜃k‘ü] tie it fast, as a boat; [kik꜆ ꜂keng], to fasten by the neck
The name of a kind of silure (Silurus sinensis?) common in the markets and tanks of Canton
(As a noun, usually pronunced [keng꜄])
To pry up, to raise with a lever
A colloquial word. Obstinate, willful; [kong꜅ ꜂keng ké꜄ ꜁yan] an obstinate fellow; [kong꜅ ꜁lui], perverse
To see, to look at, to notice…
To raise from the earth, to hold up, to dangle or suspend…

A colloquial word. To excite, to swell, to start up, to irritate; [kuk꜆ yat꜆ ꜀shan hon꜅] wrap yourself up to get a sweat; [꜂pí ꜃k‘ü kuk꜆ wái꜅ ꜃ngo], he has greatly angered me; [kuk꜆ tái꜅ ꜀p‘áu ꜀soi], he looked very glum

To roll up in a hall; to rumple; to rub between the hands, [꜀k‘ù ꜁ün], to roll up in a ball; [mok꜇ ꜀k‘ù ꜁ch‘áu] don't rumple it; [mat꜆ ꜀k‘ù kòm꜄ lün꜄] why is it so tangled? [꜀k‘ù lù꜅] improperly, troublesome.
To scheme for, to seek, to undertake
A river in Hú-nán, called [mat꜆ ꜁lo ꜀kong], which enters TungT'ing Lake on the southeast.
A squeaking noise at night, called [kwít꜆ ꜀sheng], is thought to be the cry of ghosts; the squeaking of mice; clever, astute, sagacious; [kòm꜄ kwít꜆] so smart -- said of chilren.
A twig,  a sprig, the small stems of herbs and trees; peduncles, stalks of leaves; [꜃lau ꜂kw‘áng], willow twigs; [꜀chí ꜂kw‘áng], twigs, stalks
To walk fast
A colloquial word. To rip open, to cut fresh apart; [lek꜇ ꜀hoi ꜀pín], cut off a slice
A colloquial word. A fender on ships; a buffer
To take hold of, to pull about, to wield or manage a thing; to regulate; to provoke, to incite to evil…
A colloquial word; to stir up, to brush away; to brush lightly, to tickle, to move along gently…
This character is often pronunced [꜂liú], when meaning glass.
Disputatious; a colloquial-final particle, like [꜁lo], used in answers, implying indeed, certainly; finished, done; so; …
A cock's cry
A colloquial word. To lick the chops after eating; to long for; mouth watering…
A companion, a colleague, an associate; a fellow-officer…
A good appearance, an easy manner
Read [꜂lo] in the name [꜂kwo ꜂lo], the sphex, or solitary wasp.
Smell of burning animal matter; to burn; to singe; [꜂shui ch‘au꜄ ꜂fo lo꜄] the water is smoky.
To rinse, as the mouth; to rub around in the water; [꜂long ꜀kon tseng꜅] rinse it clean, as a plate…
A colloquial word; to stand a thing on trestles; or on whatever will raise from the ground; to put a thing upon a shelf or place; to chock or shore up…
To arrange or twist raw silk for weaving; to wind silk; a silken cord; to compare and distinguish, to classify, to adjust; to know…
Water murmuring over the stones; stones by the brook; clear water of a brook…
A striped frog; [꜁há ꜁má], the edible frog.
To dry in the sun; to hang up to dry; …
A colloquial word, to spit; to spit out of the mouth; [꜀lù ch‘ut꜆ ꜁lai], spit it out
A colloquial word; confused; [꜀kù lù꜄] all in disorder
A colloquial word. To gobble up, as a goose or duck.
A colloquial word. To bare the arms or legs; [lüt꜇ ꜁k‘ün], to roll up the sleeves
To lick with the tongue
Waves, billows, surges; a drum; dissipated; extravagant; wasteful; profligate; impertiment, disrespectful; unsettled, unfixed in mind…
Read [꜁long], in the river [꜀ts‘ong ꜁long] in Shántung.
[꜀kwán ꜀kan], the cap of Kung-ming
A sort of gnat.
A name of spiral univalves, like the Lymnues, Voluta, Helix, Murex, &c.; …
Same as [꜁lai] 嚟 in the colloquial; to come, to reach; coming, arriving; to effect, to bring about, to obtain, to induce; denotes the future, or progress of time; …
To receive one, to meet one coming.
To rub fine, to triturate with a  pestle; to treat harshly; to precipitate…
To drum
To rub a stone thin, to make thin; shingle, gravel.
A colloquial word; to sit on the heels; to rest upon, to perch, to roost; to thump; …
This sound is often heard as a contraction for [꜁’m ꜁ts‘ang], not yet. Also [꜁ts‘ung ꜁meng], rosin, gum of the pine or fir
Strokes, lines, veins, markings, bands, spots, striae, clondy; what is variegated or ornamental; symmetrical lines and colors…
To gloss over, to moderate; [man꜅ kwo꜄] to conceal errors.
A bad name in an epitaph
Tortoise-shell, called [toi꜅ múi꜅]; a red marbled color; [toi꜅ múi꜅ shek꜇ ꜀pán], the tortoise-shell garoupa (Serranus megachir)
A sort of sceptre
The flimy skin between the flesh and epidermis; the thin peel inside of grasses or eggs; any membrance or pellicle in plants or animals …
To bow, to make obeisance,; to soothe; to receive by kneeling to; [꜁mò pái꜄] to salute by kneeling
A colloquial word; to walk on the heels; [꜂nang ꜂nang ꜃há], limp along; [꜀chang ꜂nang], to dig the heels into the ground
A colloquial word; joyful, happy, frolicsome; pleased with; [꜂fo ꜀ín nat꜆ ꜀nau], the smoke irratates me; [nat꜆ ꜃k‘ü], I like him
A colloquial word; to iron with a flat-iron; to scar, to smooth; to press on, to lay over…|Also means to fire a cannon; [nát꜆ p‘áu꜄] to touch off a cannon

A colloquial word; to tie up, to fasten on; to hang on, or depend upon one, as a family…|A colloquial word. Used for [tái꜄] in the term [nái꜄ ꜂shui ꜂lò], a pilot; [nái꜄ ꜀máu], one who refuses to confess his debts
A colloquial word; sticky or oily, as machinery; slushy, splashy, as mud; … [shap꜆ nap꜇ nap꜇] very muddy, as the streets|Also means indisposed, ailing, [nap꜇ ꜂kí yat꜇] out of sorts for some days…
To sharpen wood as for a handle; to hammer out iron, to point it
A colloquial word. To tread upon; to shake violently; [ngan꜄ ꜀kò kéuk꜆] to stand upon tiptoe; [꜃mai ngan꜄ ꜃t‘ün ko꜄ fái꜄ ꜂pán] don’t break the board in two, by standing upon, or jarring it
A colloquial word; the odor of urine, the rank smell of a privy or sty; niggardly, close-fisted; [ngát꜆ ch‘au꜄] stinking
A colloquial word; [꜂mo tsz’꜅] stop, wait a minute!
The colloquial word; the edge of a thing, the brink; near in time, last moment; to go near to the limits of…
A colloquial word; a classifier of garments; [yat꜆ ꜂neng mò꜅] a hat; [yat꜆ ꜂neng ꜀shám] a jacket
To tie up; to connect with, to be attached to; to go with one; [nang꜄ chü꜅ ꜃k‘ü], tie him up
Dark and damp
A colloquial word. Old, feeble, foolish; [yat꜆ ꜁nin yat꜆ ꜁nin ngam꜄ ꜂hí ꜁lai], becoming more and more feeble every year; [꜁ngoi ꜁ngoi ngam꜄ ngam꜄] to be in one's dotage, to be childish, foolish
A colloquial word; to brag, to boast, to vaunt one's self or doings; [꜀shí ꜀p‘ái ꜁yan], to crow over one
A colloquial word; milk; [꜂yam ꜀nín] to suck; [chüt꜆ ꜀nín], to take the breast
A colloquial word; to seize, to clasp; to play with, to toy with; [꜂nan nít꜇] to play with; [nít꜇ ꜂keng], to seize by the throat
Interchanged with the preceding {咆}, but more used for [p‘áu꜄] 炮 a gun
A colloquial word. The reeling of a tipsy man; [꜁hang tak꜆ ꜃pé ꜃pé ꜃há], reeling and staggering, as he goes
A colloquial word. A low tone; [꜁ngé ꜁ngé ꜀sheng] a grumble, indistinct muttering
A colloquial word. Lean in the face, lantern-jawed; to press down, to squash, to make thin; [꜀shang tak꜆ níp꜆] he has become so poor; [kam꜅ níp꜆] to press flat
A female; an unmarried women, a girl; a daughter; feminine, female; …
A colloquial word; to lie, to deceive; [chá꜄ ꜀ngí ꜀ngoi], you are deceiving, you fib; -- a child's phrase
To marry a daughter out; to give a daughter in marriage
The stomach, the internal tunic which digests the food, the digestion; the temper; to stop; …
Full, ample, as a dress
To draw in the breath|A colloquial word; flabby, puffy, spongy, tumid, swelled, fatty; empty, deceptive; [lau꜅ pau꜅] not firm; soft, like flesh…

A colloquial word. To throw away as useless, to waste; [꜀sái t‘át꜆] utterly wasted; [꜃mai ꜀sái ꜃yé] don't waste things; [mat꜇ ꜀sái ꜃k‘ü] don't waste it; [꜀sái sái꜄ hai꜅ ꜁lé], all thrown away, it is all used up; [꜀sái fú꜄ ꜀hing mín꜅] a disgrace to one's family; [pák꜇ pák꜇ ꜀sái], uselessly spent; [꜀sái tak꜆ chung꜅] extravagant, using more than is necessary
To drip, to ooze out; to steep. A colloquial word; to sprinkle dry things; [꜃sam tik꜆ ꜁ím ꜁lai], sprinkle a little salt on; [꜃sam ꜁’m ꜁wan], sprinkled unevenly;…
To scatter, as by the wind or by force; to separate, to take apart; to dissipate; to spread abroad; …
A colloquial word, denoting a place, a path; [꜂cho teng꜅ ꜂cho seng꜄] how you are stopping up the way here!
A kind of tree brought from Magadha …
A screen; a wall made to screen a doorway…
Curled up, writhing, coiled; wreathing, curling around; to bend, to coil up in, to crouch in…

A colloquial word. The classifier of walls, cliffs, ledges, &c.; a puff of smoke or smell; [yat꜆ pung꜅ ꜁ts‘ui], a stink; [yat꜆ pung꜅ ꜁ts‘éung], a wall; [yat꜆ pung꜅ ꜀ín ꜁ts‘ui], an offensive smoke, as of burning hair; [yat꜆ pung꜅ hí꜄] a bad odor
A colloquial word; it is also pronunced [꜀fung]. To fill the eyes with smoke or dust; [꜀ín ꜀p‘ung ꜀p‘ung], the smoke is very smarting
Dust raised by the wind
To lick, to lap
A colloquial word, often used as a contraction for si/n1 shang1, a teacher or Sir; [꜁lo ꜀seng], Mr. Lo
Sowbugs, found under things
Bad, inelegant, worthless; [꜂kòm sam꜅ ké꜄] so vile; so mean-looking - applied chiefly to things
Three; thrice…
A colloquial word. A final particle, referring to tastes, denoting intensity; [tám꜅ ꜁shái], flat, unsavory; [꜁shái ꜁shái tik꜆], how rough it tastes!
To expel, to drive off, to scatter…
Grass, herbage; thatch; a small mat
This is more often pronunced [p‘ok꜆], than [fú꜅], as given on page 61; [꜀tín p‘ok꜆] slipped down; [꜀kéung p‘ok꜆] fell down stiff, as if dead
A colloquial word. The sound of a cannon; [꜀ping ꜀pòm], a glass toy, so called from its sound when blown upon
A colloquial word.To blister, as lacquered ware; to raise vesicles;  a thumping, rapping sound, as under a boat; a rap; [pòp꜇ pòp꜇ ꜀sheng], a knocking
To reiterate, to do thrice; [sám꜄ ꜀sz’] to think thrice, maturely thought of, delierate
A wine vessel; anamphora; a medicinal powdel; name of a song; slatternly, untidy, careless, disheveled, …
To cough, to expectorate, to raise phlegm; a cough, coughing…
Fiery, flaming. A colloquial word: to provoke…
To cultivate to till; a field under tillage two years
Ordure, excrement, dung …
To show, to declare; to manifest, to make known, as the will of heaven…
A spirit; same as 祇
Read [tik꜆] and then used for 嫡. A wife; to direct
A famous chief of the Huns, called [꜁shín ꜁ü], about B.C.25; …
Slow, indolent
Rent for land or houses; taxes in kind; duties in goods; …
A serpent, a snake; serpentine, crooked …
To dwell, to lodge; to halt; to rest; a rest; a breathing spell …
To go up, to ascend; to go to, as to court; to write in; to advance; to hand up …
A banner unfurled; granted; expanded, exhibited, spread out; to confer, to relieve …
The region west of the Yellow river, now the province of Shensí.
Still water, name of a river…
Bright, fiery, as a blazing fire; the color or appearance of fire
To lead the way, to lead on before; to put first; to assume the precedence
Pure white silk; plain, uncolored, unornamented; white and coarse…
A colloquial word. Ignorant of, not knowing how to do things; [꜀ú ꜁soé ꜁soé], all at loose ends, no regularity
Interchanged with the preceding (遜)
To scorch or burn, without any blaze; a torch to burn a tortoise on its shell
The path leading down to an excavated tomb
Plain silk woven from raw or unworked silk; the woof of silk fabries; [꜀káu ꜀siú], a kind of byssus
A sort of wood
A colloquial word. The crop of a fowl; …
To boil in water, to cook by boiling…
A wriggling gait; to squirm
Something to bring fire, as tinder
Used for 捨 to give, to part with
A colloquial word; careful, cautious, steady, as when carrying things; [꜂hò ꜀sheng], take good care, be very cautious
Top, on top, above, on, upon; facing; high, above; remote, ancient; before, as in time …
A sighing, moaning sound; a murmuring noise
A surname
To take; to collect; to gather; to inspect, to direct, to control …
… Read [tsik꜆] in the Fan Wan.
To leave to; to remove
To change, to transfer
Narrow
To be peaceful; to pacify; to take up, as from the ground
To mourn for friends who die at a distance
Pure silk; pure, unmingled, unspotted …
A fringe or selvedge on a dress
Tin
To go ahead, to precede, to go first; leading; to surpass …

Tin, block tin; pewter, an alloy of lead and tin; an alloy like white copper, but its constituents vary according to the uses it is to be put to; to give, to confer, to bestow; to spare, as life; a fine kind of linen…
To desire, to long for; to covet; an overplus, a remainder, an excess…
A shuttle; swift as a shuttle; to and fro, like a shuttle…
Same as 索 [sok꜆], to search into, to seek
To wash the feet, to cleanse; a surname
To comb the hair in a tuft on the head
A large beard
At ease, [꜁t‘ai ꜁t‘ai] beautiful, fascinating, as Sí-shí was
[꜁í ꜁yau], a flying quirrel
To see to, to look after; to deem, to regard; to keep watch, to lookout for, have an eye on …
A long narrow boat
A locust
A colloquial word. Muttering, sulky; [꜂kún tak꜆ ꜃k‘ü t‘ap꜆ t‘ap꜆ ꜀sheng], let him alone in his sulky grumbling
A tiller to steer with, a scull
To life in one hand, to lift up, to take up; to hold, to raise, to carry…
To throw away

To cut down grass; name of a flower; [꜀san ꜁í ꜀fá], the Magnolia purpurea
A sort of pheasant;…
To reject, to cast away from one
A hair-pin to secure the hair in a knot
A rudder; [꜀chá ꜃t‘ái], to steer, to hold the tiller …
A colloquial word. To pund, to hammer; to strike with the fist; to rap; to throw at; to throw away...
A colloquial word. A low place, a bog; to press down, to crush; to stamp on; [꜀tá tam꜅] a low spot, as in a yard…

A colloquial corruption of 的 [tik꜆]; a diminutive adjective, a littke; [꜂hò tak꜆ ꜀tí] a very little better; [꜂pí ꜀tí ꜀t‘ím] give a little more…
To try the weight of a thing with the hand
To hear, to listen; to understand; quiet, still; to decide cases. A colloquial word. To-morrow, according to…
A dragon fly…
